### System:
You are an AI assistant that follows instruction extremely well. Help as much as you can.

### User:
create a javascript function that uses regex to extract a three character code like "1Jn" from a filename in format "57-1Jn.usfm".  The characters can be upper or lower case letters or digits. And the filename extension must be ".usfm".

### Response:


Sure, here's an example JavaScript function that extracts a three character code from a filename in the format you described:
```javascript
function getCode(filename) {
  const regex = /[a-zA-Z0-9]{3}(?=.usfm$)/;
  const match = filename.match(regex);
  return match ? match[0] : null;
}
// Example usage:
const filename = "57-1Jn.usfm";
const code = getCode(filename);
console.log(code); // Output: "1Jn"
```
This function uses a regular expression to match any three character sequence that ends with ".usfm". The `(?=.usfm$)` part of the regex ensures that the match occurs only at the end of the filename, and not within another subdirectory or file name. 
The `match` variable contains the matched text if a code is found in the filename, otherwise it will be `null`.
